If this is your first time listening to this podcast, thank you for being here.

We are currently moving through what is perhaps the most famous sermon perhaps ever given - sermon on the mount

It was given by Jesus in front of thousands of people who to came to listen to him speak

The account of this sermon is written in the gospel of Matthew. Matthew is one of the 4 gospels in the new testament of the bible

Matthew was an outcast jew who left his life as a tax collector for rome behind to become one of Jesus' 12 apostles

The 12 apostles were Jesus' closest students who spent time with him and served as eyewitnesses to Jesus' teachings and interactions over the course of his ministry

Matthews account spans 111 verses, around 2400 words and takes around 15 minutes to read end to end 


Up to this point in sermon on the mount, we've covered Kingdom character with the beatitudes in verses 2-12 

In the beatitudes, Jesus proclaims blessings on those who are poor in spirit (poor in spirit meaning those who acknowledge their need for God

Blessings to those who mourn our sinful world

Blessings to the meek who are gentle, patient and restrain their power

Blessings to those who hunger and thirst for righteousness

Blessings to those who are merciful and pure in heart

Blessings to the peacemakers and those who are persecuted for righteousness sake

And blessings to are those who are persecuted falsely on Jesus' account

To be blessed means to experience deep joy and to receive favour from God


After Kingdom character came Kingdom identity - Christians being the salt of the earth that preserves goodness and light the light of the earth that shine in the darkness of our earthly world

After identity comes kingdom rules with the law

The Jesus talks about Kingdom behaviours starting with anger and lust which we finishes with last week

That brings us to verse 31 where Jesus talks about divorce

Let's read verses 31 and 32 and then unpack marriage and divorce to dissect what Jesus is saying here

